WHAT IS THIS FILE
The certified display profile for Quantum Dot OLED (QD-OLED) display
technology. It defines the structure (blue OLED backplane + quantum dot
color converter), photoluminescence efficiency, emission characteristics,
color volume, peak luminance, and response time. This is the canonical
reference for GIOP ODTs targeting QD-OLED consumer and professional
monitors (e.g., Samsung QD-OLED, Sony BVM-HX3120).

WHY IT EXISTS
QD-OLED is a major emissive display technology that achieves wider color
volume than traditional WOLED by using quantum dots for color conversion.
An ODT must know the exact spectral emission of the QD layer to perform
accurate gamut mapping, and must understand its peak luminance behaviour
(which differs from LCD). This file provides the physics-based model.

HOW IT WORKS
This file specifies:
  1. Physical structure and emission principle.
  2. Quantum dot photoluminescence efficiency and emission spectra.
  3. Color primaries and color volume.
  4. Peak luminance, ABL (Auto Brightness Limiter), and sustained
     brightness.
  5. Response time and motion handling.

WHERE IT IS DEPLOYED
- High-end consumer TVs and gaming monitors.
- Professional mastering monitors (future BVM series).
- HDR consumer delivery targets.

WHO USES IT
- L2 GIOP Engineers: creating QD-OLED specific ODTs.
- L3 Colorists: mastering for QD-OLED delivery.
- Display calibration technicians.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Replaces generic "OLED" profiles with a model specific to QD-OLED's unique
spectral emission. Accounts for ABL behaviour so that ODT tone mapping can
anticipate luminance roll-off. Ensures that the wide color volume of QD-OLED
is correctly utilized.

1. PHYSICAL STRUCTURE AND EMISSION PRINCIPLE
  Structure:
    - Layer 1: Blue OLED backplane (emission peak λ ≈ 450–460 nm).
      This is a uniform layer of blue-emitting OLED pixels.
    - Layer 2: Quantum Dot color converter.
      Two types of quantum dots: one for red (peak ~630 nm), one
      for green (peak ~530 nm). Blue subpixel lets the blue OLED
      light pass through unchanged.
    - No color filter needed (unlike WOLED), so light loss is minimal.

  Emission Principle:
    Blue OLED photons (λ ≈ 455 nm) are absorbed by red and green quantum
    dots. The QDs re-emit at their design wavelengths with high efficiency.
    The quantum dot emission wavelength is tuned by nanocrystal size:
      Red QD : 5–6 nm diameter
      Green QD: 2–3 nm diameter

2. PHOTOLUMINESCENCE EFFICIENCY
  η_PL = photons_emitted / photons_absorbed
  Current generation (2026): η_PL ≈ 0.90 – 0.95 for both red and green QDs.

  Emission Spectra:
    Blue  : peak 455 nm, FWHM ~25 nm
    Green : peak 530 nm, FWHM ~30 nm
    Red   : peak 630 nm, FWHM ~35 nm

  The narrow emission spectra (compared to phosphor-based displays) yield
  very pure primaries and high color volume.

3. COLOR PRIMARIES AND VOLUME
  White Point: D65 (factory calibrated)

  DCI-P3 coverage: >99.5%
  Rec.2020 coverage: ~90% (significantly higher than WOLED at ~75%)

  CIE 1931 xy primaries (typical):
    Red   : (0.708, 0.292)  (close to Rec.2020 red)
    Green : (0.170, 0.797)  (Rec.2020 green)
    Blue  : (0.131, 0.046)  (Rec.2020 blue)

  GIOP ODT should target Rec.2020 primaries and let the display's internal
  processing map to its native gamut. Minimal gamut compression is needed
  compared to other consumer displays.

4. PEAK LUMINANCE AND ABL
  Peak Luminance:
    - 1% window  : up to 2000 cd/m²
    - 10% window : 1500 cd/m²
    - 100% full screen: 250 cd/m² (typical)

  ABL (Auto Brightness Limiter):
    The display's power supply limits total current. As the illuminated
    area increases, peak luminance decreases. The ABL curve is roughly:
      L(A) = L_peak * (1 + A/A_0)^(-1)
    where A is the fraction of screen illuminated, A_0 ≈ 0.05.
    The GIOP ODT should be aware of the mastering display's ABL curve when
    setting MaxFALL metadata. A full-frame white at 1000 nits grade (e.g.,
    for an LCD master) will be displayed at ~250 nits on QD-OLED, so a
    trim pass is recommended.

5. RESPONSE TIME AND MOTION
  Response Time    : < 0.1 ms (gray-to-gray)
  Motion Blur      : sample-and-hold blur (inherent to OLED driving method).
                     Black Frame Insertion (BFI) available in some models.
  GIOP Metadata    : Frame rate should be signaled so the display can
                     optimize its motion processing (e.g., 120 Hz BFI for
                     24p content).

6. GIOP ODT RECOMMENDATION
  Target Primaries  : Rec.2020 (display will internally map to native).
  Target EOTF       : PQ (ST.2084) for HDR, BT.1886 for SDR.
  Peak Luminance    : 2000 nit (PQ, 1% window), 250 nit sustained full-screen.
  ABL Compensation  : Provide MaxFALL metadata so the display's ABL can
                      optimize; for critical full-screen scenes, apply a
                      pre-emptive LMT that gently rolls off top-end
                      luminance.

